  "question": "A platform car of mass $M_p = 3500~\\mathrm{kg}$ moves along a straight, horizontal track with initial speed $v_0 = 2.00~\\mathrm{m/s}$ and constant acceleration $a_0 = 0.650~\\mathrm{m/s}^2$. At time $t_1 = 6.00~\\mathrm{s}$ after starting, a projectile of mass $m = 15.0~\\mathrm{kg}$ is fired from the car. In the car's reference frame (which is non-inertial and accelerating), the projectile's velocity vector is $\\vec{u}' = u'_x\\hat{\\mathbf{x}} + u'_z\\hat{\\mathbf{z}} = (21.5~\\mathrm{m/s})\\hat{\\mathbf{x}} + (17.2~\\mathrm{m/s})\\hat{\\mathbf{z}}$ where $\\hat{\\mathbf{x}}$ is along the track and $\\hat{\\mathbf{z}}$ is vertically upward. The acceleration due to gravity is $g = 9.80665~\\mathrm{m/s}^2$. The uncertainties in the car's speed at firing and the projectile's velocity components (relative to the car) are $\\sigma_{v_{\\text{car}}} = 0.12~\\mathrm{m/s}$, $\\sigma_{u'_x} = 0.08~\\mathrm{m/s}$, and $\\sigma_{u'_z} = 0.10~\\mathrm{m/s}$, respectively; these are uncorrelated and random, and the uncertainties in $v_0$, $a_0$, $t_1$, and $g$ are negligible. Neglecting air resistance, recoil, and any change in the car's motion due to firing (assume both car and projectile remain point particles), and assuming the projectile lands at the same vertical level as it was fired, compute the propagated standard uncertainty $\\sigma_R$ in the horizontal range $R$ of the projectile as measured in the stationary ground frame.\n\nGive your answer for $\\boxed{\\sigma_R~[\\mathrm{m}]}$ rounded to three significant digits.",
  "topic_tags": [
    "kinematics",
    "relative motion",
    "projectile motion",
    "error propagation",
    "advanced mechanics"
  ]
}

logs.improved_question:
{
  "question": "A railway platform car moves in a straight horizontal line on frictionless tracks. At time $t=0$, it has a known velocity $v_0 = 2.00~\\mathrm{m/s}$ and constant acceleration $a = 0.650~\\mathrm{m/s}^2$ (both in the $+x$ direction, with $+x$ parallel to the track and $+z$ vertically upward in the laboratory frame). At time $t_1 = 6.00~\\mathrm{s}$, an experimenter on the car launches a small projectile from a point at height $z=0$ above level ground. The projectile's velocity relative to the car's instantaneous rest frame (an inertial frame momentarily moving with the car at speed $v_{\\text{car}} = v_0 + a t_1$) is measured as $\\vec{u}\\;' = (u'_x)\\,\\hat{\\mathbf{x}} + (u'_z)\\,\\hat{\\mathbf{z}}$, with $u'_x = 21.5~\\mathrm{m/s}$ and $u'_z = 17.2~\\mathrm{m/s}$ (both positive, and uncertainties as below). Neglect all effects of air resistance, recoil, and the projectile mass; assume the car's motion is unaffected by the launch. \n\nThe experimenters determine $v_{\\text{car}}$, $u'_x$, and $u'_z$ from independent electronic measurements, and their standard uncertainties (one standard deviation, uncorrelated and Gaussian) are $\\sigma_{v_{\\text{car}}} = 0.12~\\mathrm{m/s}$, $\\sigma_{u'_x} = 0.08~\\mathrm{m/s}$, and $\\sigma_{u'_z} = 0.10~\\mathrm{m/s}$. Uncertainties and correlations in all other parameters ($v_0$, $a$, $t_1$, $g$) are negligible. Local gravitational acceleration is $g = 9.807~\\mathrm{m/s}^2$ (exact for this problem).\n\nFor this experiment, the horizontal range $R$ is defined as the $x$-coordinate displacement (in the stationary laboratory frame) between the point of firing and the point where the projectile next crosses $z=0$. \n\nUsing the first-order (linear) propagation of uncertainty, and assuming all relevant uncertainties are uncorrelated and random, compute the standard uncertainty $\\sigma_R$ in the measured range $R$. Express your final answer as $\\boxed{\\sigma_R~[\\mathrm{m}]}$ rounded to three significant digits.",
  "topic_tags": [
    "projectile motion",
    "relative motion",
    "reference frames",
    "error propagation",
    "advanced mechanics"
  ]
}

